<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'SLEEPLESS IN SEATTLE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Michael Wilmington 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Writer-director Nora Ephron's terrifically popular 1993 release is a real 
charmer, a romantic comedy about an ultimate long-distance relationship.The 
"Sleepless" lovers -- Tom Hanks as Sam, an insomniac Seattle widower-architect, 
and Meg Ryan as Annie, a Baltimore journalist -- not only live in different 
cities on different coasts, they don't even know each other. They connect 
through a national call-in radio show. Ephron's quick-quip take on talk-radio 
make her film contemporary, but she also returns us to the great days of the 
American romantic comedy. With Ross Malinger as Sam's tug-at-our-hearts son, 
Jonah. (Showtime Sunday at 8 p.m.; Saturday at noon and 8 p.m.) Michael 
Wilmington 
</P>
</TEXT>
