<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'BRAM STOKER'S DRACULA' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This enjoyable 1992 release might be more aptly titled "Francis Coppola's 
Dracula," for Coppola brings to the umpteenth retelling of Stoker's 1897 novel 
the grand operatic style of his "Godfather" movies -- plus considerable 
sensuality and affectionate tongue-in-cheek play.Gary Oldman (pictured) is 
suitably world-weary as Dracula, and Winona Ryder (pictured) his winsome 
principal victim. The starry cast includes Anthony Hopkins, Keanu Reeves and 
most memorably, Tom Waits as Renfield, the grotesque early victim of the 
Transylvanian count. A lush period production, with Eiko Ishioka winning an 
Oscar for her opulent costumes. (HBO Monday at 8 p.m.) Kevin Thomas 
</P>
