<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLETCHER JONES, CAR DEALER, DIES AT 76 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fletcher Jones, a colorful car dealer who built a chain of agencies from a 
single Los Angeles lot, died Thursday in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
 He was 76.At the time of his death from what his family described as natural 
causes, Jones had amassed an organization of 11 domestic- and foreign-car 
dealerships in California and Nevada -- a long way from selling his first 
automobile for $70. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1992, Jones purchased a bankrupt Mercedes-Benz dealership in Newport Beach 
and asked his son, Fletcher (Ted) Jones Jr. to run it. Called Fletcher Jones 
Motor Cars in Newport Beach, the dealership is now the second largest Mercedes 
dealer in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
 His son is married to Las Vegas Mayor Jan Jones. 
</P>
<P>
 From his start at a Chrysler-Plymouth dealership in Los Angeles in 1950, the 
elder Jones' business grew rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
 He became omnipresent in the early days of television advertising, smiling and 
cuddling puppies and kittens on camera and offering to send a portion of his 
auto sales profits to animal shelters. 
</P>
<P>
 Jones opened his first Nevada dealership in Las Vegas in 1966. In 1992, Auto 
Age 500 reported his dealerships as the 12th largest group in the country. 
</P>
<P>
 He attended USC on a basketball scholarship and opened his first car lot with 
only $1,200 in capital. 
</P>
<P>
 Survivors include his sons Fletcher Jr. and Robert; daughters Stephanie and 
Bonnie, and 10 grandchildren. 
</P>
</TEXT>
