<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: TROVATTEN NAMED AS FOOTBALL COACH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF FLETCHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jeff Trovatten has been named head football coach at St. Genevieve High. 
Trovatten, 40, replaces Richard Fong, the 1993 Times Valley football coach of 
the year, who left St. Genevieve after last season to take an assistant 
coaching position at Crespi. 
</P>
<P>
 Trovatten, who was an assistant softball coach at College of the Canyons last 
year, headed the Hart junior varsity football team in 1991 and 1992, compiling 
a 15-5 record and winning one Foothill League title. He was also an assistant 
junior varsity football coach at Hart for two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
 Trovatten inherits a team that went 9-3 last season and was unbeaten in Camino 
Real League play. Baseball  
</P>
<P>
 Chris Beck, a right-handed pitcher from The Master's, has signed with the 
Seattle Mariners and will be assigned to the Mariners' short-season Class-A 
team in Bellingham, Wash., he said Saturday. Beck, the Mariners' seventh-round 
pick in the draft earlier this month, was 5-7 in his senior year with the 
Mustangs this season. 
</P>
<P>
 Adam West, a left-handed pitcher out of Thousand Oaks High and Pierce College, 
has signed with the St. Louis Cardinals and will play for the Cardinals' team 
in the rookie-level Arizona League. 
</P>
<P>
 West, who was drafted in the 30th round, will simply move from Scottsdale, 
Ariz., where he was playing for the Scottsdale Braves in the Arizona Collegiate 
League, to Chandler, Ariz., site of the Cardinals' affiliate. West, who was 
10-4 with a 2.95 earned-run average for the Brahmas in 1994, opted to sign 
rather than accept a scholarship to University of the Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
 Cardinal scout Chuck Fick, who signed Tighe Curran last year, has now signed 
both left-handers from the Newbury Oaks American Legion team that he coached to 
the World Series title in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 "When I first became a scout, I said it would be nice if I could sign my two 
best left-handers," Fick said. "It's a dream for me. If I could see them 
pitching in the big leagues in five years, it'd be a great story." JEFF 
FLETCHER 
</P>
