<TEXT>
<P>
 LESSONS IN SURVIVAL by Laramie Dunaway (Warner: $19.95; 424 pp.) It's like 
eating chocolate truffles. A lot of them. For breakfast. Laramie Dunaway is 
clever, witty, mordant, ripe with repartee and riposte. So are her characters: 
The prodigy, the principal, the producer, the teller, the cop on the beat, all 
emit epigrams like B.O. In the middle of sex: "I'm trying not to think." "How 
do you do that?" "Become a Republican." While fleeing the police in a tense 
scene: "Don't make fun of lepers." "Sorry . . . the dermatologically 
disadvantaged." Four hundred pages of when sally met parry. It gets crowded. 
</P>
<P>
 All of which detours attention around a bang-up story, full of acute 
commentary on the human condition of the '90s whenever Dunaway stops to inhale. 
The plot thickens on Page 1, with Blue Erhart hounded by the tabloids at the 
school where she teaches biology (in a style vivid enough to rate a book by 
itself). After 20 years in the slammer, her bank-robber parents -- "kind of a 
hippie version of Bonnie and Clyde" with unloaded shotguns, who'd mailed their 
withdrawals to worthy causes -- are being released. The doting parents had 
brought 10-year-old Blue along on the heists, presumably on the theory that the 
family that preys together stays together. Blue remains resentful, especially 
of Mom, who'd declined parole 10 years earlier in a gesture of solidarity with 
Dad. Free at last, Blue's folks, bored, rob a bank two days later. Blue, 
burdened, pursued by movie deals, decamps for the Bend, an Arizona retreat 
where there are no rules, no messages, just a casual messiah called Thomas Q -- 
whose perfection is underscored by his opinion of Grandpa Walton: "I never did 
trust him. He had a weird look in his eye, like he had some very racy magazines 
stuffed under his mattress." And this is just a sample. 
</P>
<P>
 Everyone gets together, more or less, Blue ending up with a wanna-be producer, 
to whom she has the gall to say: "Can't you just speak to me? No clever patter, 
no snappy dialogue." Jeez. 
</P>
</TEXT>
