<P>
 THE SEWING ROOM by Barbara Cawthorne Crafton (Penguin: $12.99; 253 pp.). One 
of the first women to be ordained into the Episcopal priesthood, Crafton offers 
her reflections on the joys and frustrations of her pastoral duties.In her 
efforts to care for the homeless in New York, she learns that chemical 
dependency and mental illness often thwart the best intentions of both 
care-givers and patients. A cheerful account of a Christmas service for foreign 
sailors takes a chilling turn when many of the men who attended are lost in a 
storm. It's easy to understand how the resistance some parishioners felt toward 
the idea of a female priest soon gave way to acceptance: Even on the printed 
page, Crafton exhibits an almost palpable charm. 
