<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SOUTH: USC AREA; CHILDREN'S CLINIC OPENS AT NEW SITE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LUCILLE RENWICK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a symbolic gesture linking the Los Angeles Child Guidance Clinic to the 
South-Central area that it serves, more than 200 city officials, business 
people and community leaders tied together strips of ribbons Thursday as part 
of the dedication of the clinic's new facility. 
</P>
<P>
 "Children in L.A. County have really been the ones to suffer from disasters 
that hit us . . . so a center like this and a place where (clinic staff) can 
provide a sense of guidance is really crucial in L.A.," County Supervisor 
Yvonne Brathwaite Burke said. 
</P>
<P>
 The peach-colored, $9.6-million structure has allowed clinic officials to 
expand services and classes for the more than 100 children, most of them black 
and Latino, use the clinic each day.  
</P>
<P>
 The clinic, which celebrates its 70th anniversary this year, opened at its new 
location on South Vermont Avenue in May. LUCILLE RENWICK 
</P>
