<HEADLINE>
<P>
ART: GALLERY OWNER REPLIES TO COMMENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In response to the letter written by Mae Gabriel-Brax on June 5, 1994, I would 
just like to say that Ms. Gabriel-Brax, who considers herself my competitor, is 
mistaken or misinformed. We have been in business for close to four years and 
hold regularly scheduled exhibits of works by emerging and museum-stature 
artists.Galerie Lakaye participates in prestigious art fairs around the country 
(Art L.A., Chicago International Art Exposition), frequently hosts lectures on 
Haiti and Haitian art, and I often create exhibits for the Los Angeles Cultural 
Affairs Department. 
</P>
<P>
 We do not sell lingerie, jewelry and dishes at Galerie Lakaye. I believe Ms. 
Gabriel-Brax refers to a Christmastime event which I organize with my friends 
every year, when we get together and sell gift items for fun, and hopefully 
profit. I have been doing this for years before even opening the gallery, and 
it has become a much-anticipated event by friends and clients alike (this 
gallery is my home too). 
</P>
<P>
 Finally, I would like to extend my thanks and appreciation to all the friends, 
patrons and art connoisseurs who, in the face of detraction, continue to show 
their support and loyalty to Galerie Lakaye. 
</P>
<P>
 CARINE FABIAS 
</P>
<P>
 Owner, Galerie Lakaye  
</P>
<P>
 Hollywood  
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061994-0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 052865 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
June 19, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
