<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND FIRMS DOMINATE GOLD NUGGETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Southern California home builders and architects have won 16 of 37 Grand 
Awards in the Gold Nugget design competition at the 1994 Pacific Coast Builders 
Conference (PCBC) & Remodelers Show, the annual meeting of developers and 
allied professionals from the 14 Western states and Pacific Rim countries. 
</P>
<P>
 Southland builders, designers and projects again dominated the Gold Nugget 
contest, although not by as wide a margin as in the past. Last year, by 
contrast, 22 grand awards went to Southern Californians or their works. 
</P>
<P>
 The design contest was the highlight of the 36th annual PCBC, one of the 
largest building industry conventions in the United States, which ended 
Saturday at the Moscone Convention Center here. 
</P>
<P>
 The Gold Nugget Award competition honors achievements in architecture and 
land-use planning for residential, commercial and industrial projects. This 
year's contest attracted 450 entries. 
</P>
<P>
 Judges were chairman Peter M. Mayer, president of Peter M. Mayer Productions 
of Alta Loma, Calif.; Philip M. Hove AIA, principal of CYP International, 
Irvine; Sandra Kulli, president of Kulli Marketing, Malibu; Larry Kush, 
president of Saddleback Homes, Scottsdale, Ariz.; Jim McKellar, publisher of 
Sun/Coast Architect/Builder, Glendale; Dan McLeister, senior editor of 
Professional Builder, Des Plaines, Ill.; Victor Mirontschuk of EDI 
Architecture, Houston; Lynn Pomeroy, AIA, principal of LPA Inc., Sacramento, 
and Chris Stuhmer, president of Christopher Homes, Las Vegas. GRAND AWARD 
WINNERS 
</P>
<P>
